<article>
    <h1>HE CAN WALK UNAIDED AGAIN</h1>
    <h2>With fam&#xAD;ily sup&#xAD;port, stroke sur&#xAD;vivor over&#xAD;came neg&#xAD;a&#xAD;tiv&#xAD;ity and un&#xAD;der&#xAD;went reg&#xAD;u&#xAD;lar ther&#xAD;apy</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201026/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-26"><time>2020-10-26</time></a>
        - <span>HOME</span>
        - <span role="byline">Chong Jun Liang&#xD;&#xA;Ex&#xAD;ec&#xAD;u&#xAD;tive Pho&#xAD;to&#xAD;jour&#xAD;nal&#xAD;ist&#xD;&#xA;jun&#xAD;liang@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Mr Ed­die Tan wryly calls Nov 14, 2017, his new birth­day. That was the day he suf­fered a stroke, chang­ing his life for­ever.</p>
    <p>It was a rou­tine morn­ing, with Mr Tan, now 56, work­ing on the lap­top in his bed­room. But the first sign of trou­ble soon hit. At about 9.15am, he tried to push up his spec­ta­cles and re­alised he had lost con­trol of his left hand.</p>
    <p>Feel­ing be­wil­dered, he tried to stand but fell im­me­di­ately.</p>
    <p>The pos­si­bil­ity of a stroke crossed his mind. But he did not act on his in­stincts and de­cided to just rest on the floor in­stead of call­ing for his son, who was at home at the time.</p>
    <p>Some eight hours passed be­fore his wife raised the alarm, af­ter a friend told her that Mr Tan was un­con­tactable. His son im­me­di­ately checked his par­ents’ room and found his dad ly­ing flat on the floor.</p>
    <p>Even then, Mr Tan was re­luc­tant to go to the hos­pi­tal. He said he wanted to “just lie in bed and rest for a while”, and that he “would be fine af­ter a rest”. Thank­fully, his fam­ily did not abide by his wish.</p>
    <p>He was taken to Changi Gen­eral Hos­pi­tal, where he was di­ag­nosed with a haem­or­rhagic stroke caused by bleed­ing in the brain.</p>
    <p>The left side of his body was badly af­fected and he lost con­trol of his left limbs.</p>
    <p>Mr Tan be­came de­spon­dent and sui­ci­dal, es­pe­cially since he was an ac­tive per­son prior to the stroke and en­joyed out­door ac­tiv­i­ties such as fish­ing.</p>
    <p>But with strong fam­ily sup­port, he was able to slowly over­come the neg­a­tiv­ity.</p>
    <p>Mr Tan put in the hard work for re­cov­ery by reg­u­larly at­tend­ing phys­io­ther­apy and oc­cu­pa­tional ther­apy ses­sions at All Saints Home’s and Abil­i­ties Beyond Lim­i­ta­tions and Ex­pec­ta­tions’ re­ha­bil­i­ta­tion cen­tres.</p>
    <p>To­day, he is walk­ing again, al­beit with a slight limp, and en­cour­ages stroke pa­tients at Ang Mo Kio-Thye Hua Kwan Hos­pi­tal as part of a be­frien­der pro­gramme.</p>
    <p>He also be­lieves in rais­ing stroke aware­ness, es­pe­cially the im­por­tance of seek­ing im­me­di­ate med­i­cal at­ten­tion at the first sign of stroke. He rues his own de­lay in seek­ing help, and some­times won­ders if his own con­di­tion might have been bet­ter had he called for help ear­lier.</p>
    <p>Staff Sergeant Muham­mad Hariz, a para­medic with the Sin­ga­pore Civil De­fence Force, said: “Time is of the essence. Any one of the stroke symp­toms such as face droop­ing, arm weak­ness and speech dif­fi­culty war­rants an im­me­di­ate call to the emer­gency num­ber 995.”</p>
    <p>Ev­ery minute counts. For i nstance, I V tPA, a clot-bust­ing medicine given in­tra­venously to is­chaemic stroke pa­tients, can­not be ad­min­is­tered once 41/ hours have</p>
    <p>2 passed af­ter the stroke oc­curred. An is­chaemic stroke is caused by a block­age in an artery that sup­plies blood to the brain.</p>
    <p>Stroke vic­tims are ad­vised to call for an am­bu­lance in­stead of get­ting to the hos­pi­tal on their own. Paramedics are trained to pro­vide ba­sic treat­ment and can in­form the hos­pi­tal to have the nec­es­sary med­i­cal team ready to re­ceive the stroke pa­tient.</p>
    <p>Glob­ally, one in four adults over the age of 25 will suf­fer from a stroke in their life­time. The ill­ness is also the fourth most com­mon cause of death in Sin­ga­pore.</p>
    <p>As the world marks World Stroke Day on Thurs­day, check if you are at risk and act if nec­es­sary.</p>
    <p>A healthy life­style, a bal­anced diet and man­ag­ing risk fac­tors such as hy­per­ten­sion, high blood choles­terol, di­a­betes, smok­ing and ir­reg­u­lar heart­beat will go a long way in pre­vent­ing a stroke.</p>
    <p>DON’T WAIT TO CALL FOR HELP</p>
    <p>Time is of the essence. Any one of the stroke symp­toms such as face droop­ing, arm weak­ness and speech dif­fi­culty war­rants an im­me­di­ate call to the emer­gency num­ber 995.</p>
    <p>STAFF SERGEANT MUHAM­MAD HARIZ, a para­medic with the Sin­ga­pore Civil De­fence Force, on what to do in the event of a stroke.</p>

